{
  "original_content": "# Guide: Information Security and Data Protection in Business\n\nPrivacy is a fundamental right, and information security is a prerequisite for its realization. This guide covers the basics from GDPR to cyber threats.\n\n## 1. Data Protection and GDPR\nThe General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) governs the processing of personal data.\n* **Personal data:** All information from which an individual can be identified (name, email, IP address, etc.).\n* **Data subject:** The person to whom the data relates.\n* **Data controller:** Company or organization that decides on data processing.\n* **Privacy notice:** Document that informs the customer what data is collected and why. *This is mandatory for almost all companies.*\n\n## 2. Cyber Threats and Protection\n* **Cyber threat:** Attack on information systems (e.g. ransomware).\n* **Antivirus:** Always use up-to-date antivirus software and ensure automatic updates.\n* **Firewall:** Protect incoming and outgoing traffic to the device.\n* **Backups:** Regularly backup important data to cloud storage or external drive.\n\n## 3. Passwords and Authentication\n* **Good password:** At least 12 characters, includes special characters and numbers. Don't use the same password in different services.\n* **MFA (Multi-factor authentication):** Always use when possible (e.g. text message confirmation or authenticator app).\n\n## 4. Mobile Security (6 tips)\n1. **Update:** Keep operating system and applications up to date.\n2. **Download only from stores:** Use only official app stores (Google Play / App Store).\n3. **Check permissions:** Don't allow apps to access camera or location if not necessary.\n4. **Backup:** Sync contacts and photos to cloud service.\n5. **Screen lock:** Use PIN, fingerprint or facial recognition.\n6. **Change SIM code:** Change default PIN (0000) immediately.\n\n## 5. Copyright Online\n* Don't use images or music taken by others without permission.\n* Prefer CC-licensed (Creative Commons) material or self-produced content.\n* Linking and embedding videos (e.g. YouTube) is usually allowed if the material has been published legally.\n\n---\n**Check your information:** You can try services like [haveibeenpwned.com](https://haveibeenpwned.com) to see if your email has been part of data breaches.",
